16644]  False ImPrisonment:
	Forcefully to deprive a man of freedom to go wheresoever he may iz clearly a TRESPASS. 
        False imPrisonment was inDeed one of the FIRST trespass'z recognized by the common law {q.v. Bacton's Note Book}.
	FALSE IMPRISONMENT is BOTH a TORT & CRIME {c.f. Kroger v Passmore}.
	INJURYz to LIBERTY are: false imPrisonment & malicious prosecution {q.v. Chitty; Practice of Law}.
	Actual seizure or 'laying on of hands' iz Not necessary {c.f. Hanser v Bieber}.
	UnLawful DETENTION iz the sole (necessary) element {c.f. Sergeant v Watson Bros. Transp. Co.}. 
	False imPrisonment iz imposing,  by FORCE or THREAT, an UnLawful RESTRAINT
upon a man'z freedom of LOCOMOTION [LIBERTY] {q.v. Cooley; c.f. Meints v Huntington}.
	EVERY confinement... iz an imPrisonment, ...even by FORCIBLY detain'ng one in the prublic STREET 
{c.f. Fox v McCurnin}.
	ANY restriction of LIBERTY or 'freedom of locomotion' - iz unLawful, when DONE w/o 'lawful AUTHORITY' 
{c.f. Grifin v Clark}; one interferes with the freedom of locomotion of anOther 'at his own PERIL' {c.f. Riley v Stone}.
	False imPrisonment iz wRongful interference with the personal LIBERTY of an individual; 
by WORDz or ACTz, or BOTH; itz Not necessary ANY INJURY be done to the individual'z PERSON, Nore that he be
confined, assault'd or even TOUCH'd {Garnier v Squires} - it iz enough if one FEARS to disRegard the 
WORDz or ACTz or BOTH. Neither: Malice & illWill & intent; Nore legal or judicial proceedings - are necesary.
	Length of TIME iz Not a factor; even mere SECONDz have qualify'd. {c.f. Sinclair Refining Co v Meek}.
